ant legal progress made with the adoption of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms, the traditional legal definition of "persons" continues to limit the legal, social, economic, and political freedom of queer people.Using an interdisciplinary approach, Lahey presents a historical analysis of litigation relating to sexuality and of the most recent constitutional decisions on sexuality in Canada and the United States. Further discussion concerns immigration law, inheritance law, and same-sex marriage, as well as the widespread exclusion of queers from government census and other statistical surveys.Are We "Persons" Yet? provides an excellent model for the analysis of discrimination on the basis of sex, race, sexuality, and marital status and a valuable reference for academics and activists alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBisexualsxLegal status, laws, etczCanada. 0aBisexualsxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanada. 0aCross-dressersxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanada. 0aGaysxLegal status, laws, etczCanada. 0aGaysxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanada. 0aTranssexualsxLegal status, laws, etczCanada. 0aTranssexualsxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanada. 0aTransvestitesxLegal status, laws, etczCanada. 7aLAW / Gender & the Law.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267095240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442670952423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442670952.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPD